00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:50.620
then it could be any one of the
crystals that comes out of the 14

00:21:50.620 --> 00:22:08.840
Bravais lattices, plus
a range of bases.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:41.000
There is a huge database out there
that has values of intensity versus

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:47.000
angle for thousands and thousands of
metals and compounds.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:53.000
A huge amount of mineralogy in this
database. And so,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:59.000
when you bring a specimen of unknown
provenance, you are able to use this

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.000
technique and infer what
the constituents are.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:31.750
First of all, let's take a look at
what the specimen looks like.

00:22:31.750 --> 00:22:49.066
I cannot take a few atoms. What we
use is a powdered specimen.

00:22:18.500 --> 00:22:45.250
We grind the material into a fine
powder and we put it in a silicate

00:22:45.250 --> 00:23:02.966
glass holder. And a silicate glass
holder looks something like this.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:55.730
It is a very narrow tube.
This is definitely not to scale.

00:22:55.730 --> 00:22:59.460
This dimension here is about a
tenth of a millimeter.

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:03.190
It is a very narrow tube,
a tenth of a millimeter made of

00:23:03.190 --> 00:23:06.930
silicate glass.
It is an oxide glass,

00:23:06.930 --> 00:23:10.660
a cousin of window glass.
Why do we choose it? Not because

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:14.390
it is transparent visible light.
We don't care. We are shooting

00:23:14.390 --> 00:23:18.130
x-rays through this thing,
for heaven's sakes. Why do we

00:23:18.130 --> 00:23:22.830
choose this?
Because it is amorphous and it

00:23:22.830 --> 00:23:28.490
doesn't have a crystal structure of
its own. If we are trying to

00:23:28.490 --> 00:23:34.160
irradiate the contents of this and
the tube itself has a crystal

00:23:34.160 --> 00:23:39.830
structure, how are we going to sort
out what is the contents from the

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:45.490
container. This is amorphous,
no long range order. And inside we

00:23:45.490 --> 00:23:51.160
put little grains of powder.
The powder dimension is on the

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:55.920
order of about 50 micrometers.
Oh, the wall thickness,

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:59.780
I didn't mention that. That is one
one-hundredth of a millimeter.

00:23:59.780 --> 00:24:03.640
Saying it is paper thin is an
exaggeration. It is one-hundredth

00:24:03.640 --> 00:24:07.490
of a millimeter.
And this distance is about two

00:24:07.490 --> 00:24:11.350
centimeters. You grind in a mortar
and pestle, drop the powder in here,

00:24:11.350 --> 00:24:15.210
and this goes into the
diffractometer and is irradiated.

00:24:15.210 --> 00:24:19.070
And we are going to turn this in
order to present as many different

00:24:19.070 --> 00:24:22.810
angles as possible.
We have many grains in here.

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:26.430
Each grain, the theory is if we
grind these fine enough,

00:24:26.430 --> 00:24:30.060
each one of these can act as a
single crystal.

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:33.680
Now light is coming in and
reflecting off this,

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:37.300
but its cousin is sitting at a
slightly different angle.

00:24:37.300 --> 00:24:40.930
And so I am going to try to,
through the mix of powder and the

00:24:40.930 --> 00:24:44.560
rotation of the specimen,
try to get all of the different

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:48.180
incident angles so that I will get
as many reflected angles as possible.

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:51.820
I worked with this.
It was my PhD thesis.

00:24:51.820 --> 00:24:55.460
The material was sensitive to
moisture in the air so I had to work

00:24:55.460 --> 00:24:59.110
in a glove box.
I had these big thick rubber gloves

00:24:59.110 --> 00:25:02.760
on holding something like this.
Only in real life it is about this

00:25:02.760 --> 00:25:06.400
big. And you are inside the glove
box and it's Toronto in August and

00:25:06.400 --> 00:25:10.050
perspiration is pouring.
You are supposed to be crying now.

00:25:10.050 --> 00:25:13.700
The perspiration is pouring down my
face. I have to get the powder to

00:25:13.700 --> 00:25:17.350
fall in here. And I have got to
flick this a little bit.

00:25:17.350 --> 00:25:36.500
I flick it one more time and it
breaks off.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:25.830
You laugh now.
It's not funny.

00:25:25.830 --> 00:25:30.660
That's the way. That's how science
goes. Anyway.

00:25:30.660 --> 00:25:35.490
What happens now?
We take this. Now I am going to

00:25:35.490 --> 00:25:40.330
give you the top view of the
diffractometer.

00:25:40.330 --> 00:25:45.160
It is essentially the combination
of an x-ray generator,

00:25:45.160 --> 00:26:04.720
a specimen holder and a detector.
The top view has x-ray coming in.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:35.500
This is monochromatic x-ray,
some lambda fixed, coming in.

00:25:35.500 --> 00:25:41.000
Top view has this sitting in a
carousel, and this carousel spins.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:46.500
And then I have a detector. And
the detector itself moves through a

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:52.000
variety of angles.
And so here we have an incidence

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:57.500
angle and here we have a reflectance
angle. Ultimately,

00:25:57.500 --> 00:26:03.000
we get a plot of intensity versus
reflected angle from this specimen.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:07.000
That is how this thing works.
And here is what the output could

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:11.000
look like. You will have nothing
and then you will have peaks at

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:15.000
discrete lines.
Why? At certain angles the Bragg

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.000
condition is satisfied.
At other angles the Bragg condition

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:23.000
is not satisfied.
These are the Bragg peaks

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:27.000
associated with magical angles.
And what are the magical angles?

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.000
They are the angles associated with
those planes.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:55.130
This is how we are trying to make
sense of what is going on here.

00:26:55.130 --> 00:26:59.260
I wanted to give you the thrill of
discovery, so we are going to do a

00:26:59.260 --> 00:27:03.390
virtual lab here.
What I have for you is a data set.

00:27:03.390 --> 00:27:07.530
If you flip over your sheet, this
is all you get,

00:27:07.530 --> 00:27:11.660
the output. Now,
for reasons I don't want to go into,

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:15.790
the angles are often reported as two
theta instead of theta.

00:27:15.790 --> 00:27:19.930
And it has to do with the geometry
of this specimen and

00:27:19.930 --> 00:27:23.750
blah, blah, blah.
But that is not important.

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:27.250
We have a copper target in the
x-ray generator,

00:27:27.250 --> 00:27:30.750
which means we will have
monochromatic light lambda 1.

00:27:30.750 --> 00:27:34.250
418 angstroms. We know that. And,
remember, we said we had to fix our

00:27:34.250 --> 00:27:37.750
lambda. We have done that.
We have rotated the specimen

00:27:37.750 --> 00:27:41.250
variable theta.
And these are the peaks.

00:27:41.250 --> 00:27:44.750
I don't care about the intensities.
All I am doing right now is telling

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:48.250
you these are the peaks that I got.
How do we take that and infer what

00:27:48.250 --> 00:27:51.760
the crystal is?
Well, you can go to the library and

00:27:51.760 --> 00:27:55.290
get all these self-help books.
I have not had the time to write a

00:27:55.290 --> 00:27:58.820
full self-help book,
but I got this one self-help sheet

00:27:58.820 --> 00:28:02.350
here. This is my program.
You won't find this in any books.

00:28:02.350 --> 00:28:05.880
This I am giving to you special. I
want to walk through this and show

00:28:05.880 --> 00:28:09.410
you how to take that dataset and
index the crystal.

00:28:09.410 --> 00:28:12.940
The question we are trying to
answer is what is the crystal

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:16.460
structure? And you only have three
answers. It's either going to be

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:36.653
simple cubic, body-centered cubic or
face-centered cubic.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:25.270
And that is the dataset.
That is all you have, plus your

00:28:25.270 --> 00:28:30.540
mind. It says start with the two
theta values and generate a set of

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:35.810
sine squared theta values.
Oh, I should perhaps tell you how I

00:28:35.810 --> 00:28:41.080
came up with this,
what is the underlying principle.

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:46.360
Here is the underlying principle.
To solve the puzzle, all I did was

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:51.810
I took these two equations.
I took the Bragg's Law,

00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:57.450
which is lambda equals 2 d sine
theta, and I took the formula for

00:28:57.450 --> 00:29:03.090
the d spacing between planes,
which you saw two days ago, which is

00:29:03.090 --> 00:29:08.720
the ratio of the lattice constant
divided by the sum of the squares of

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:14.360
the Miller Indices of the plane.
If I take those two equations and

00:29:14.360 --> 00:29:32.386
put them together,
I can get the following relationship.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:05.000
Lambda squared over 4 a squared
equals sine squared theta over h

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:10.000
squared plus k squared plus l
squared. Now,

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:15.000
look at the left side of this
equation. Lambda is the wavelength

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:20.000
of the incident radiation,
and that is fixed. We fixed that in

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:25.000
the experiment,
so this is a constant.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:30.000
It is fixed. A is the lattice
constant of the crystal.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:54.140
That is the crystal property,
so that is fixed. That means the

00:29:54.140 --> 00:29:58.280
ratio of lambda squared over 4 a
squared is a constant.

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:02.420
Well, when I went to school,
what they taught me in math was that

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:06.560
if the left-hand side of the
equation is constant,

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:10.710
the right-hand side of the equation
is constant. That means even though

00:30:10.710 --> 00:30:14.850
theta is varying with hkl,
this ratio varies in such a way as

00:30:14.850 --> 00:30:33.033
to remain constant.
That is the key.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:23.420
Whatever hkl is,
at that theta, the sine squared of

00:30:23.420 --> 00:30:27.850
that angle over the h squared plus k
squared plus l squared remains

00:30:27.850 --> 00:30:32.280
constant as you go through all of
the lines. This is the underlying

00:30:32.280 --> 00:30:36.710
principle. Let's go into this.
The first thing I want to do is

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:41.140
build sine squared theta.
There they are. Those are the

00:30:41.140 --> 00:30:45.560
theta values. And now I have taken
them, divided them by two and then

00:30:45.560 --> 00:31:05.053
taken the sine and then squared it.
Now I have a new column.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:54.300
And then it says normalize by
dividing sine squared theta by the

00:30:54.300 --> 00:30:58.610
first member of the column.
All I did was took everything and

00:30:58.610 --> 00:31:02.920
divided it by 0.
43. This 0.143 divided by 0.

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:07.230
43 is one. This is, as you can see,
0.190 divided by 0.140 is about 1.34

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:11.530
and so on. Why?
Because, look, I am going to this.

00:31:11.530 --> 00:31:15.840
What is the next thing? Clear the
fractions from the normalized column.

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:34.080
I don't like this.
I don't like 1.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:23.390
0, 1.34 and so on.
1.34 to me, allowing for some

00:31:23.390 --> 00:31:26.990
experimental error,
is roughly one and a third.

00:31:26.990 --> 00:31:30.590
It is roughly four-thirds. And
that is 2.67. That is roughly

00:31:30.590 --> 00:31:34.190
eight-thirds. Why not multiply the
whole darn column by 3 and throw

00:31:34.190 --> 00:31:37.790
away the little residuals.
And, sure enough, you get a set of

00:31:37.790 --> 00:31:41.390
whole numbers,
3, 4, 8, 11, 12 and so on.

00:31:41.390 --> 00:32:00.313
This is good. We are getting
somewhere.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:49.660
Now it says speculate,
this is where you get to participate,

00:31:49.660 --> 00:31:54.330
on the hkl values that if expressed
as h squared plus k squared plus l

00:31:54.330 --> 00:31:58.990
squared would generate the sequence
of the clear fractions column.

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:03.660
And remember what you have to go on.
You have that set of simple cubic,

00:32:03.660 --> 00:32:08.330
face-centered cubic, body-centered
cubic. What set of hkl's would give

00:32:08.330 --> 00:32:12.990
you this? Well,
what sum of integer squares would

00:32:12.990 --> 00:32:17.660
give you three?
I wonder. Maybe 1,

00:32:17.660 --> 00:32:22.060
,1. How about 4?
And so you can see what is going on

00:32:22.060 --> 00:32:26.190
here. This I have gotten from the
theta, and this is my speculation,

00:32:26.190 --> 00:32:30.330
just trying. And now here is the
punch line. Compute for each theta

00:32:30.330 --> 00:32:34.460
the value of this.
The sine squared theta over h

00:32:34.460 --> 00:32:38.590
squared plus k squared plus l
squared. And,

00:32:38.590 --> 00:32:42.730
if you get a constant,
bingo, you must have hit the jackpot.

00:32:42.730 --> 00:32:46.860
Sine squared theta is this.
H squared plus k squared plus l

00:32:46.860 --> 00:33:05.586
squared is square root
of 3. That is 0.0477.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:55.920
You do it for the next one,
the next one and next one allowing

00:32:55.920 --> 00:33:00.840
for experimental error.
I have a constant. What does that

00:33:00.840 --> 00:33:05.760
say? It says that my speculation of
what the hkl's are is good.

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:10.690
It is self-consistent. And what do
I know? Those are either all even

00:33:10.690 --> 00:33:15.610
or all odd. That is the sequence
for face-centered cubic.

00:33:15.610 --> 00:33:20.530
So, on this basis, I can say that I
have something that is

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:38.360
face-centered cubic.
I am happy about that.

00:33:05.500 --> 00:33:10.500
But, furthermore, what else can I
get? Well, I know the lambda value

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:15.500
and I know this thing.
This is that constant there.

00:33:15.500 --> 00:33:20.500
What I can do is take this constant
and plug it into this equation.

00:33:20.500 --> 00:33:25.500
And, furthermore, I can determine
that the a, whatever this crystal is,

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:30.500
is going to be lambda of copper k
alpha divided by 2 times the square

00:33:30.500 --> 00:33:55.250
root of that constant.
And, if I plug in the numbers,

00:33:55.250 --> 00:33:59.750
I get 3.53 angstroms. It is FCC.
It is 3.53 angstroms. If I look at

00:33:59.750 --> 00:34:04.250
it and it looks metallic,
I am going to say it is nickel,

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:08.750
because I happen to know that nickel
has a lattice constant of 3.

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:13.250
3 angstroms. I know I have to do
some other things,

00:34:13.250 --> 00:34:17.750
but certainly that makes me think
about whether I have nickel present.

00:34:17.750 --> 00:34:22.610
Here is the gambit.
That is how you are going to solve

00:34:22.610 --> 00:34:27.840
these problems.
You are going to go through this

00:34:27.840 --> 00:34:33.070
set of operations.
Just to recap, if you are going to

00:34:33.070 --> 00:34:38.300
look at this, simple cubic,
the hkl sequence is 1, 2, 3,

00:34:38.300 --> 00:34:43.530
4, 5, 6, 8, 9, because there is no
sum of integers that will give you

00:34:43.530 --> 00:34:48.760
seven if you sum squares of integers.
It will give you all the lines,

00:34:48.760 --> 00:35:08.186
but this is h squared plus k squared
plus l squared in ascending value.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:59.090
Body-centered cubic has to be 2,
4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16. But, when

00:34:59.090 --> 00:35:04.180
you first do this,
you don't know because you divide by

00:35:04.180 --> 00:35:09.270
the first sine squared.
And so you don't know it is 2,

00:35:09.270 --> 00:35:14.360
4, 6, 8. You could end up with 1,
2, 3, 4. Now, don't we have a

00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:19.450
problem? The simple cubic is going
1, 2, 3, 4 and body-centered cubic

00:35:19.450 --> 00:35:24.330
is going 1, 2, 3, 4.
But watch this,

00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:28.990
perseverance. Half of 10 is 5.
Half of 12 is 6. Half of 14 is 7.

00:35:28.990 --> 00:35:33.660
Bingo. If you guessed that
something when you divide through

00:35:33.660 --> 00:35:38.330
you get a sequence that gives you 1,
2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, you know that it

00:35:38.330 --> 00:35:42.990
cannot be simple cubic because there
is no sum of integer squares that

00:35:42.990 --> 00:35:47.660
gives you 7. This 7,
in fact, must be 14 divided by 2.

00:35:47.660 --> 00:35:52.300
This is body-centered cubic.
Face-centered cubic is the easiest

00:35:52.300 --> 00:35:56.920
one to pick off because it gives you
3, 4, 8, 11, 12.

00:35:56.920 --> 00:36:01.530
I mean, I just need to see 3,
4 and I am done. I always check for

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:06.150
FCC first. Anyway,
that is how diffractometry works.

00:36:06.150 --> 00:36:10.760
And it allows you to index crystals
and determine their crystal

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:15.380
structure. And,
more broadly speaking,

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:35.293
there is a database of all sorts of
minerals and compounds and so on.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:06.000
Let's look at the second technique
which is called Laue diffraction

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:12.000
named after Max von Laue who got the
Nobel. He was the first person to

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:18.000
demonstrate x-ray identification of
crystal structure.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:24.000
He got the Nobel in 1912 for this.
And in Laue we fix the angle, the

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:30.000
specimen is stationary and variable
wavelength radiation.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:34.000
How do we get variable wavelength
radiation? Look at that spectrum up

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:38.000
there. You see the bremsstrahlung?
The bremsstrahlung gives you a

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:42.000
range of wavelengths.
How do we get monochromatic

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:46.000
radiation? How do we get
monochromatic x-rays?

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:50.000
And don't tell me we buy an x-ray
laser. How do we get monochromatic

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:54.000
x-rays? Well,
it is really cool.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:58.000
What you do is take this
bremsstrahlung with

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:22.260
everything on it.
And you present it to a single

00:37:22.260 --> 00:37:26.790
crystal. And then you park over
here, this is the entrance slit to

00:37:26.790 --> 00:37:31.330
your diffractometer.
What will go through that entrance

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:35.860
slit? There is only one wavelength
that will go through that entrance

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:40.390
slit, and that is the wavelength
that satisfies the Bragg condition

00:37:40.390 --> 00:37:44.930
for this lattice spacing at this
angle. What I can do is make a

00:37:44.930 --> 00:37:49.460
single crystal monochromator that
basically takes this characteristic

00:37:49.460 --> 00:38:07.386
spectrum on top of the
bremsstrahlung.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:59.190
Sends that in.
I present a single crystal.

00:37:59.190 --> 00:38:04.390
And there is only one wavelength of
light that will come out of here

00:38:04.390 --> 00:38:09.590
that satisfies the Bragg condition
for this d spacing and this angle.

00:38:09.590 --> 00:38:14.790
The single crystal acts as a
monochromator.

00:38:14.790 --> 00:38:33.313
Very cool. This is called a single
crystal monochromator.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:06.000
Just use Bragg's Law.
That is all. Well, in this case,

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:12.000
we take the whole mess, everything.
And here is what the specimen looks

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:18.000
like. The specimen goes into a
darkened box called a "camera

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:24.000
obscura." And what happens is I can
put the specimen on the front here.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:30.000
This is some crystal, relatively
thin.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:55.450
And I put film on the back.
I have film that is sensitive to

00:38:55.450 --> 00:39:00.900
x-ray. Now I send the beam in.
This is white x-ray meaning it is

00:39:00.900 --> 00:39:06.360
variable wavelength.
It is the whole spectrum.

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:11.810
And what happens is the white x-ray
interacts with the specimen and

00:39:11.810 --> 00:39:17.270
shoots off at different angles
because I have different

00:39:17.270 --> 00:39:35.640
initial wavelengths.
Each wavelength will be diffracted

00:39:02.500 --> 00:39:07.500
at its own special angle.
What happens is we end up with a

00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:15.000
spot pattern on the film.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:40.110
Spot pattern is the output.
And the symmetry of the spot

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:45.220
pattern. I am not going to take you
into k space and so on,

00:39:45.220 --> 00:39:50.330
but let me simply tell you that all
you need to appreciate at this point

00:39:50.330 --> 00:39:55.440
is that the symmetry in the spot
pattern is imitative of the symmetry

00:39:55.440 --> 00:40:00.870
in the crystal.
Let me say something about atomic

00:40:00.870 --> 00:40:06.620
symmetry. And all we are talking
about here is rotational symmetry

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:12.370
because we are looking at something
on edge. For example,

00:40:12.370 --> 00:40:18.120
if I gave you the 001 plane,
in a cubic crystal it looks like

00:40:18.120 --> 00:40:23.210
this.
Now what I want to do is look at

00:40:23.210 --> 00:40:27.640
rotation about a normal axis.
I am going to put a normal axis

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:32.070
right here at the center,
and I am going to rotate this.

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:36.490
I am going to ask you the question
through what angle do I have to

00:40:36.490 --> 00:40:40.920
rotate this in order to get this
back? If you close your eyes and I

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:45.350
start rotating,
suppose I rotate it 45 degrees,

00:40:45.350 --> 00:40:49.780
you open your eyes, you are going to
see that and know something

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:54.330
has moved.
How many degrees do I have to rotate

00:40:54.330 --> 00:40:58.990
before I get this back?
90. If I rotate 90 degrees,

00:40:58.990 --> 00:41:03.660
I will end up with this. These are
indistinguishable.

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:08.330
90 degrees is what I need to rotate.
And the crystallographers,

00:41:08.330 --> 00:41:12.990
instead of talking about the angle
of rotation to restore what you are

00:41:12.990 --> 00:41:17.660
looking at, they talk about fold.
And fold is simply 360 degrees

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:35.786
divided by this angle.
We say that this has four-fold

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:09.000
rotational symmetry.
Suppose I look at (011).

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:15.000
(011) is the diagonal. This is a
and this is square root of 2a.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:21.000
And now, if I put an axis in the
center, through what angle do I have

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:27.000
to rotate before I get this back?
That is 180. This has two-fold

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:52.330
symmetry.
Finally, let's do (111).

00:41:52.330 --> 00:41:56.990
The (111) plane looks like this.
And so, obviously, this you would

00:41:56.990 --> 00:42:01.660
have to go through 120.
And this would exhibit three-fold

00:42:01.660 --> 00:42:06.330
symmetry. For example,
remember I showed you that crystal

00:42:06.330 --> 00:42:10.990
of the silicon,
single crystal silicon?

00:42:10.990 --> 00:42:15.660
The single crystal silicon,
let's say we have cut it and we want

00:42:15.660 --> 00:42:35.920
to find out what plane we cut it on.
Suppose we want to insure that we

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:04.000
have cut it so that the 111 plane is
parallel to the surface.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:08.000
One way of determining this would
be to put the single crystal of

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:12.000
silicon into a Laue unit and
irradiate it. And,

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:16.000
if indeed we have the 111 plane,
we will see a spot pattern that

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:20.000
exhibits three-fold symmetry.
This allows us to do indexing.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:24.000
The other thing we can do is put
the specimen on the back and have

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:28.000
the film on the front.
And we end up with what is known as

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:52.300
Laue backscatter.
Let's take a look at a few more

00:42:52.300 --> 00:42:56.920
symmetries. This is going back to
some Escher prints.

00:42:56.920 --> 00:43:01.530
I don't think I showed you this one
the other day.

