00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:22.870
Now I am going to show you something
that was really,

00:46:22.870 --> 00:46:26.740
really unexpected.
So far we are over here in the top

00:46:26.740 --> 00:46:30.620
left. We are studying ordered
solids which they have a unit cell,

00:46:30.620 --> 00:46:34.490
they are periodic, and we call them
a crystal. And pretty soon we are

00:46:34.490 --> 00:46:38.370
going to start studying disordered
solids which form glasses.

00:46:38.370 --> 00:46:42.240
In 1982, there was a fellow by the
name of Dan Schechtman who was on

00:46:42.240 --> 00:46:46.120
sabbatical from the Technion in
Israel. He was working down at the

00:46:46.120 --> 00:47:06.306
National Bureau of Standards.
It was called NBS in those days.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:53.850
It is now known as the National
Institute of Standards and

00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:57.710
Technology. Sometimes you will see
this acronym NIST.

00:46:57.710 --> 00:47:01.560
And they were down in Gaithersburg,
Maryland. And Schechtman and John

00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:05.420
Kahn and coworkers were looking at a
set of alloys from the aluminum

00:47:05.420 --> 00:47:09.280
manganese system,
and they were very highly ordered.

00:47:09.280 --> 00:47:13.140
Over the range of composition, pure
aluminum is FCC.

00:47:13.140 --> 00:47:32.346
Pure manganese has multiple crystal
structures.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:20.680
The question is what happens when
you take something that is not

00:47:20.680 --> 00:47:24.360
face-centered cubic and alloy it
with something that is face-centered

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:28.050
cubic? Well, initially aluminum
retains its face-centered cubic

00:47:28.050 --> 00:47:31.730
crystal structure.
But, after a while,

00:47:31.730 --> 00:47:35.420
you get to such a high manganese
level that the crystal structure

00:47:35.420 --> 00:47:39.100
changes. And over certain ranges of
composition these alloys are

00:47:39.100 --> 00:47:42.780
amorphous. They are glass formers.
But then came something totally

00:47:42.780 --> 00:47:46.470
unexpected. When Schechtman
prepared the alloy that contained

00:47:46.470 --> 00:47:50.150
25% manganese he got something
extremely weird in the x-ray

00:47:50.150 --> 00:48:09.766
diffraction pattern.
He got five-fold symmetry in his

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:38.000
x-ray diffraction pattern.
Five-fold symmetry. This lax

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:42.000
translational symmetry,
it is aperiodic, these were termed

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:46.000
quasicrystals.
And this caused a storm in the

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:50.000
material science community.
In the mid 80s, all kinds of NSF

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:54.000
programs, Department of Defense
programs were funding research into

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:58.000
quasicrystals to try to figure out
they might have some

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:22.660
unique properties.
Maybe they have conductivities.

00:48:22.660 --> 00:48:27.990
Maybe they have ductilities. Maybe
they have corrosion resistance that

00:48:27.990 --> 00:48:33.330
is unknown in classical
face-centered,

00:48:33.330 --> 00:48:38.660
body-centered, simple cubic alloys.
Here is one of Schechtman's Laue

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:43.990
patterns. Look at that.
That is so weird. There were jokes

00:48:43.990 --> 00:48:49.330
about this. If you know the
geography, Gaithersburg is not far

00:48:49.330 --> 00:48:54.540
from Washington.
Some people joked that this had

00:48:54.540 --> 00:48:59.630
five-fold symmetry because the
research was funded by the Pentagon.

00:48:59.630 --> 00:49:04.720
And this is really something.
These are the pages from

00:49:04.720 --> 00:49:09.810
Schechtman's lab notebook.
April 8, 1982, aluminum 25%

00:49:09.810 --> 00:49:14.900
manganese. And he is analyzing his
diffraction patterns and is going

00:49:14.900 --> 00:49:33.066
nuts. He writes ten-fold
exclamation point triple.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:23.860
And it was real.
It was very, very exciting.

00:49:23.860 --> 00:49:27.730
That is what quasicrystals are
about. What you can see is how

00:49:27.730 --> 00:49:31.590
using Laue you can infer that.
And then you have to go in and

00:49:31.590 --> 00:49:35.460
determine what the lattice constant
is and so on. The last thing,

